In .NET MAUI, you configure platform lifecycle events in `CreateMauiApp()` using `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android => android
            .OnPause(activity => HandleBackground())
            .OnStop(activity => HandleBackground()));
#elif IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios => ios
            .DidEnterBackground(app => HandleBackground()));
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}

static void HandleBackground()
{
    // your background logic here
}
```

**Key points:**
- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`
- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code separated
- **Android**: `OnPause` fires when partially obscured, `OnStop` when fully hidden
- **iOS**: `DidEnterBackground` covers both cases

Each platform exposes its full set of native lifecycle events (e.g., `OnResume`, `WillEnterForeground`, etc.) through the same API.
